Vulnerability: IDOR
Target: API Endpoint (/api/user/)
Impact: Unauthenticated users can delete any arbitrary account on the platform.

Description:
The application exposes its API documentation at /api/. By analyzing the documentation, it was discovered that the /api/user/[username] endpoint accepts DELETE requests.
The endpoint relies on the session cookie for authentication but fails to implement proper authorization checks, allowing an attacker with any valid session to delete other users accounts.

Steps to Reproduce (PoC):

1 - Map API Endpoints: Intercept the application's normal traffic using Burp Suite to identify API interactions.

2- Discover API Documentation: Send a GET request to /api (which returns a 302 Found), and then to /api/ (which returns a 200 OK containing the full API documentation).

3- Identify the Target Route: Review the documentation to find that the API accepts DELETE requests at the /api/user/[username] endpoint.

4 - Attempt Direct Access (Failed): Send a direct DELETE /api/user/carlos HTTP/2 request without session cookies. Observe the 401 Unauthorized response, indicating that a valid session is required.

5 - Capture a Valid Session: Log into your own account (e.g., wiener) and perform a profile update (like changing the email). Intercept this request in Burp Suite to capture the PATCH /api/user/wiener HTTP/2 request, which includes your valid session cookie.

6 - Exploit the Vulnerability: Send the intercepted request to Burp Repeater. Change the HTTP method from PATCH to DELETE and modify the target path from your username to the victim's username (/api/user/carlos).

7 - Confirm Execution: Send the modified request. The server returns an HTTP/2 200 OK with the body {"status":"User deleted"}, successfully bypassing authorization and deleting the target account.
